Introduction¶

This report is dedicated to visualization and analysis of stock price data of companies listed on Borsa Istanbul. The primary goal of this analysis is to understand the market dynamics and assess the performance of individual companies. To achieve this, we have examined stock price data for six companies from varying sectors, focusing on the years 2015 and 2016. The companies are as follows: AEFES, AKBNK, MGROS, CCOLA, THYAO, SISE. The objective is to uncover patterns, outliers, and potential correlations within their stock price data. Firstly, for each company, boxplots are generated for each month. Additionally, 3-sigma limits for each month are calculated and if the number of outliers accounted for more than 1% of the data, an exploration into the relationship between stock prices and Google Trends data is conducted, aiming to reveal insights into potential connections between online search behavior and stock market trends during the specified years. The threshold is set as 1% to decrease the number of graphs in the report.

The Code and Explanations¶

Firstly, the necessary Python libraries are imported: pandas for creating and manipulating dataframes, numpy for mathematical calculations and matplotlib.pyplot for data visualization.

Functions¶

4 functions are used to manipulate and visualize the data:

  1. boxplot_generator: Accepts the stock price data, start_year, end_year, start_month, end_month, and the stock name as parameters, drops NA values, and plots boxplots for each month in the specified timeframe.

  2. compare_price_and_trends: Accepts the Google Trends data, the stock price data, start_year, end_year, start_month, end_month, and the stock name as parameters, drops NA values, normalizes and plots both data in the same graph in the specified timeframe. Both data are normalized for better visualization.

  3. outlier_calculator: Accepts the stock price data, start_year, end_year, start_month, end_month, and the stock name as parameters, drops NA values, and for each month, computes the mean, standard deviation, control limits based on 3-sigma limits, and plots the control chart if the outliers account for more than 1% of the data.

  4. prepare_trends_data: Accepts Google Trends data as parameter and prepares it for further use.

In [5]:
# Function to plot the boxplots of a stock between two dates
def boxplot_generator(df=df, start_year=2015, end_year=2016, start_month=1, end_month=12, stock_name="AEFES"):

    all_data = []

    for i in range(start_year, end_year + 1):
        for j in range(start_month, end_month + 1):
            filtered_data = df[(df.timestamp.dt.month==j) & (df.timestamp.dt.year==i)]
            filtered_data = filtered_data[["timestamp", stock_name]]
            filtered_data.dropna(inplace=True)
            all_data.append(filtered_data[stock_name])
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(24, 7))
    ax.boxplot(all_data, flierprops={'marker': '.', 'markerfacecolor': 'red', 'markersize': 8})
    ax.set_xticklabels([str(i) + "-" + str(j) for i in range(start_year, end_year + 1) for j in range(start_month, end_month + 1)])
    ax.set_ylabel("Price")
    ax.set_xlabel("Year-Month")
    ax.set_title("Boxplots of " + stock_name + " between " + str(start_year) + "-" + str(start_month) + " and " + str(end_year) + "-" + str(end_month))
In [6]:
# Function to plot the Google trends data and price of a stock between two dates
def compare_price_and_trends(trends_data, df=df, start_year=2015, end_year=2015, start_month=2, end_month=2, stock_name="AEFES"):

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))

    for i in range(start_year, end_year + 1):
        for j in range(start_month, end_month + 1):
            filtered_data = df[(df.timestamp.dt.month==j) & (df.timestamp.dt.year==i)]
            filtered_data = filtered_data[["timestamp", stock_name]]
            filtered_data.dropna(inplace=True)
            filtered_data[stock_name] = (filtered_data[stock_name]-filtered_data[stock_name].mean())/filtered_data[stock_name].std()
            trends_data["Interest"] = (trends_data["Interest"]-trends_data["Interest"].mean())/trends_data["Interest"].std()
            ax.plot(filtered_data["timestamp"], filtered_data[stock_name], label="Price")
    ax.plot(trends_data["Day"], trends_data["Interest"], color="red", label="Trend")
    ax.legend()
    title = f"{start_month:02d}-{start_year} {stock_name}"
    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

# Function to calculate the monthly outliers of a stock and plot the monthly stock prices if outliers account for more than 1% of the data
def outlier_calculator(df=df, start_year=2015, end_year=2016, start_month=1, end_month=12, stock_name="AEFES"):
    for i in range(start_year, end_year + 1):
        for j in range(start_month, end_month + 1):
            filtered_data = df[(df.timestamp.dt.month==j) & (df.timestamp.dt.year==i)]
            filtered_data = filtered_data[["timestamp", stock_name]]
            filtered_data.dropna(inplace=True)
            mean = np.mean(filtered_data[stock_name])
            standard_deviation = np.std(filtered_data[stock_name])
            lower_limit = mean - 3 * standard_deviation
            upper_limit = mean + 3 * standard_deviation
            outliers = filtered_data[(filtered_data[stock_name] < lower_limit) | (filtered_data[stock_name] > upper_limit)]
            outlier_percentage = len(outliers) / len(filtered_data) * 100
            if len(outliers) > 0 and outlier_percentage > 1:
                print(f"{i}-{j}:\nMean of {stock_name} prices: {mean:.2f}\nStandard deviation of {stock_name} prices: {standard_deviation:.2f}\nNumber of outliers = {len(outliers)}\nPercentage of outliers = {len(outliers) / len(filtered_data) * 100:.2f}%\n")
                fig, axs = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
                axs.set_title(f"Stock prices of {stock_name} in {i}-{j}")
                axs.set_ylabel("Price")
                axs.set_xlabel("Date")
                axs.plot(filtered_data["timestamp"], upper_limit * np.ones(len(filtered_data)), color='red', label="Upper Control Limit")
                axs.plot(filtered_data["timestamp"], lower_limit * np.ones(len(filtered_data)), color='blue', label="Lower Control Limit")
                axs.plot(filtered_data["timestamp"], mean * np.ones(len(filtered_data)), color='orange', label="Mean")
                axs.plot(filtered_data["timestamp"], filtered_data[stock_name], color='black', label="Stock Price")
                axs.legend()
In [8]:
# Function to prepare the Google trends data for plotting
def prepare_trends_data(data):
    data = pd.read_excel(data)
    data["Day"] = pd.to_datetime(data["Day"])
    return data

AEFES:

The boxplots of AEFES between January 2015 and December 2016 are shown below. There are outliers in February 2015, August 2015, October 2015, December 2015, January, 2016, April 2016, May 2016, July 2016, October 2016, and December 2016.

February 2015, August 2015, and May 2016 have numerous outliers. The reason for the outliers in February 2015 may be connected to international events. According to the news reports at that date, decreasing oil prices have affected companies that have businesses in Russia negatively. AEFES was one of them, so its stock prices decreased. That fast decrease created some outliers. In August 2015, the whole stock market was down and there was significant volatility. This was probably the result of terror attacks in the country. In May 2016, the stock market saw heavy losses again. It was probably the result of the resignation of the prime minister.

THYAO:

The boxplots of THYAO between January 2015 and December 2016 are shown above. A general decline starting in late 2015 and continuing into 2016 is observed in the first glance at the box plots. Based on a general industry research and company statements, it has been found that Turkish Airlines (THYAO) performed poorly in 2016 due to adverse developments believed to have a direct impact on air transportation, such as geopolitical risks and global security concerns in the regions where THYAO operates.

Monthly examination reveals several outliers in June 2015, October 2015, November 2015, December 2015, August 2016, September 2016, and November 2016. When a more detailed examination is conducted for the months in which outliers occurred, there is only one month, September 2016, in THYAO data that, according to 3-sigma limits, outliers account for more than 1% of the data.

The boxplots of AKBNK between January 2015 and December 2016 are shown above. There are outliers in February 2015, June 2015, October 2015, December 2015, May 2016, and November 2016. February 2015, June 2015, October 2015, and November 2016 have numerous outliers. The outliers in February 2015 are the result of the significant decrease in the price. The outliers in June 2015 seem to be different as the mean for June is not very different from the mean for May. The outliers may be the result of price volatility and the volatility may be the result of the general elections on June 7th that didn’t give any party the power to form a government. The outliers in October 2015 are the result of the significant increase in the price, and the outliers in November 2016 are the result of the significant decrease in the price, once again.

Monthly examination reveals several outliers in January 2015, Macrh 2015, January 2016, February 2016, March 2016, April 2016, May 2016 and December 2016.

Although not perfectly aligning on specific days of the month, there are similar trends and directions in both search patterns and prices. Additionally, considering May 1st is both a weekend and a special holiday in our country and the recent record-low level of the dollar, it is thought that the week started with a high but stabilized afterward due to these factors.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, the analysis of stock price data for selected companies listed on Borsa Istanbul reveals intriguing patterns and outliers in specific months. Anomalies, possibly influenced by external factors, are detected for all companies employing boxplot and 3-sigma approaches, and potential reasons are investigated. While certain correlations with Google Trends are explored, the presence of external factors and the complexity of market behaviors makes it challenging to establish definitive links between stock prices and Google Trends data.
